{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:35:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1800"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1800"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.13,0.62,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109032"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1800"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"985"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2108"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40708"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109032"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe epigastric pain radiating to his back. He has a long history of alcohol dependence with minimal engagement with health services. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals epigastric tenderness with guarding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT abdomen shows haemorrhagic and necrotising pancreatitis. He is managed with supportive measures in the Intensive Care Unit. Four days after admission, several small petechiae are noted all over his body. Blood tests reveal haemoglobin 97 g/L (135-180), platelets 80 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450), activated partial thromboplastin time 60 seconds (24-38), and international normalised ratio 2.4 (0.9-1.2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following results would be expected on further investigations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased haptoglobin","Positive direct antiglobulin test","Decreased fibrinogen","Anisocytosis on blood film","Positive serotonin release assay"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with severe acute pancreatitis has developed disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), evidenced by petechiae, thrombocytopenia, and prolonged coagulation times. DIC involves the widespread activation of the coagulation cascade, leading to the consumption of clotting factors and platelets, resulting in both bleeding and thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased fibrinogen\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs due to consumption during the coagulation process, is a key component of the International Society on Thrombosis and Haemostasis (ISTH) scoring system for DIC. The criteria includes:  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eplatelet count (\u0026lt;100 = 1 point, \u0026lt;50 = 2 points)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eelevated fibrin markers such as D-dimer (moderate increase = 2 points, strong increase = 3 points)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eprolonged coagulation times (\u0026gt;3 seconds but \u0026lt;6 seconds = 1 point, \u0026gt;6 seconds = 2 points)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efibrinogen level (\u0026lt;1.0 g/L = 1 point). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA score \u22655 is compatible with overt DIC. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased haptoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected in DIC. Haptoglobin is an acute-phase reactant that may be elevated in inflammation but is typically decreased in haemolytic anaemia due to binding with free haemoglobin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive direct antiglobulin test\u003C/strong\u003E detects antibodies or complement bound to red blood cells and is used to diagnose autoimmune haemolytic anaemia, which is not consistent with this clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnisocytosis on blood film\u003C/strong\u003E refers to red blood cells of varying sizes and is a non-specific finding seen in various types of anaemia, but is not characteristic of DIC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive serotonin release assay\u003C/strong\u003E is a functional test used to confirm heparin-induced thrombocytopaenia, which is not relevant to this patient\u0027s presentation of DIC secondary to pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Disseminated intravascular coagulation is a severe complication of acute pancreatitis characterised by abnormal bleeding and clotting.","The ISTH scoring system for DIC includes platelet count, elevated fibrin markers, prolonged coagulation times, and decreased fibrinogen levels.","Decreased fibrinogen is a key laboratory finding in DIC due to consumption during the coagulation process."],"references":["Taylor, F. ISHT Criteria for Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation (DIC) . In: MDCalc [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.mdcalc.com/isth-criteria-disseminated-intravascular-coagulation-dic.","Papageorgiou C, Jourdi G, Adjambri E, Walborn A, Patel P, Fareed J, et al. Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation: An Update on Pathogenesis, Diagnosis, and Therapeutic Strategies. Clin Appl Thromb Hemost. 2018;24(9):8S-28S. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30296833/","Warkentin TE, Arnold DM, Nazi I, Kelton JG. The platelet serotonin-release assay. Am J Hematol. 2015;90(6):564-72. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25775976/#:~:text=Few%20laboratory%20tests%20are%20as,4%20(PF4)%2Fheparin%20antibodies"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1800"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:01:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:02:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1800"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109032"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only 